You could simply put your `new Function` code inside an `else` block:
```
if (typeof Function == &#39;undefined&#39;) {
  location.href = &#39;old-browsers.html&#39;;
} else {
  var f = new Function(&#39;return true;&#39;);
}
```

**Edit 2:** It would be a much cleaner design to check if a feature is supported *when the feature is about to be called*. This would make it easier to work with multiple JS files.

The initial approach I posted works fine if all code is in one JS file, but may cause problems whe multiple JS files are in play (a function may be called before the compatibility checking).

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    if(function1) { //if function1 is supported
      function1();
    }
    else {
      location.href = &#39;some_link.hmtl&#39;;
    }

    //function2 could be in a separate JS file

    if(function2) { //if function2 is supported
      function2();
    }
    else {
      location.href = &#39;some_link.hmtl&#39;;
    }

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


----------


Your code as is should work without raising errors, if you put it all in a single `&lt;script&gt;` tag.



**Edit:** Turns out no need for the code to be in the same script tag either; your approach as is should work fine.

Javascript is an ***interpreted*** language, not a ***compiled*** one, meaning that statements will be evaluated one by one at runtime. Therefore, if the browser is too old, one of the if conditions should be satisfied and the `location.href` line will execute immediately, without looking at the function calls after it.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;!-- feature check --&gt;
    &lt;script&gt;
    if (typeof Function == &#39;undefined&#39;) {
        // this line will immediately redirect, and the code below it will not be reached
        location.href = &#39;old-browsers.html&#39;;
    }

    //using the functions
    var f = new Function(&#39;return true;&#39;);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

